Four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of heated debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is more relevant today than ever. Looking back on events since 9/11, I have personally seen mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance for Islam in America. I don’t think in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who has a clear Muslim background in his family.
The Biography of the Prophet intrigues me because, according to what I know of the history of Muhammad, the biography contradicts the personality of Muhammad. From what I know and have learned in the past, I thought that Muhammad forced conversions to Islam. He would conquer and take over tribes and then force them to adopt the Islamic religion. However, according to the biography, Muhammad is depicted as a sort of martyr who was misunderstood and even humbled himself to others. After which, one by one, people came to see the ‘truth’ in his teachings and sought him out.
Moreover, there are uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the ‘miracles’ of Muhammad. The most obvious is when he multiplied mutton and milk so that there was more than enough for forty men. It is this style of writing that makes me believe the writers wanted Muhammad to be perceived as the humble prophet who needed not to prove anything, but simply lived in truth and miracles. This sort of fallacy is the worst because it diminishes the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it is like they are stealing and trying to take credit for the life and personhood of Jesus through Muhammad.
Additionally, there are many stories in the biography that give the impression that part of their agenda is to provide proof of ‘witness’ or of how people ‘on their own’ converted to Islam. However, the problem is that many of the stories are at least from a third-party perspective. That is, in the story, the author illustrates that he heard from so-and-so who heard from so-and-so, etc. I didn’t like this much because although their intention was to provide proof of the truth of the stories, I thought it diminished the stories and made them seem more suspicious.
What bothers me the most about this work is that they try to exalt and elevate Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. However, history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can’t help but think if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad’s rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his beliefs during his lifetime were quickly abandoned in the development of Christian thought that followed his life. Upon examining this history in a broad sense, we can see a tendency for Christianity to stray further and further from its origins. The world today exhibits an ever-growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive trend. While traditional people exist and will resist any new ideas, their influence may not be significant enough to sway the whole. Within the Christian community, historical awareness will grow in the coming years. There will be a desire to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the original intent of Christianity's namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: there will be a great reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a return to its original form. A movement will grow, removing layer after layer of doctrine, as if the clock were turning back, until nothing remains except a concept of what Jesus brought to humanity from God, before anyone else made such claims. When this trend spreads through the United States and Europe, influencing the masses to worship as if it were the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church will remain strong to lead the way. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the extreme diversity of Christendom will reverse into more uniformity of belief and practice. Among regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is filled with reversals. For example, Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country went from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversal coming in the future will play out in the arena of the Christian religion, undoing history to find the source and reducing diversity in the process. It is important to note that part of what will make this process possible is reading Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. So, what happened since Jesus' lifetime?
       If we go back far enough in history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning of Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures, were all at the core of the religion by the time the Romans took over Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united in spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that The Jungle shows how human beings deep down inside are naturally greedy and self-centered. They only want to look out for themselves and make their lives as good as possible, but never look out for anyone lower than themselves. The Jungle shows this in many ways. The main obvious area is the owners and managers of the great factories. All they want to do is make their companies and factories as big and great as they can be. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets in their way or anything that gets hurt because of their advancements.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude towards important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald employs many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to create a certain aura around a subject. Other times, he assigns meaning to a symbol and then uses it for the same purpose. Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In his novel The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, specifically white/gray and red/pink, and later uses this meaning to remind readers of a feeling around an important object.

The meaning Fitzgerald assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white being slightly nicer and higher class and gray being older and faded. Fitzgerald establishes this meaning at the beginning of the novel with constant use of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors by coloring many common, unimportant subjects with them: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61) on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27). After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy. After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character, more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition, for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is exceptionally fertile, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, stone fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. The region has a strong market for organic community-supported agriculture, with many local organizations experiencing long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms offer tours of their agricultural operations, as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. These types of operations can help landowners gain access to government programs while enhancing habitat, allowing recreational use and creating opportunities for farm tours and educational programs. In addition to filling a potentially profitable niche market, organic farming often promotes greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals. However, it requires more intensive labor and management to control pests, weeds, and fertilize the soil without chemicals, leading to higher costs compared to conventional farming. Losses can also be greater with small-scale organic farms, which lack the efficiency of large operations. Practices beneficial to wildlife, such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth, may further increase labor costs. Therefore, landowners might seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize both profits and habitat quality. The land in question is a 160-acre parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. This land includes chaparral, non-native Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. It is located within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which currently considers over a hundred plant and animal species, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher. This area was inhabited by Native Americans for centuries and later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This particular parcel was part of an original homestead patent, likely used for grazing or wood production for many decades. The land was chosen from a real estate website, and available government programs for small-scale farmers were researched to explore cost mitigation and wildlife-friendly operation options. A nearby organic farm was used as a model for potential operations on this land.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be understood not only by what it is, but also by what it is not and what it signifies. Culture is not homogeneous, neither is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Generalizations like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are overly broad and simple. While understanding these generalizations is appropriate, it is more productive for a negotiator to understand the significance of culture to the matter at hand and how that cultural attitude will affect the table talk. When approaching a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that relates to their own culture, and comparisons naturally arise. Trying to understand a foreign culture or mindset might involve studying its history or recognizing its prejudices. Instead of judging or trying to change a culture, one must accept it for what it is and work within its boundaries, especially in the context of negotiation, and especially if one is in a weaker bargaining position. If a negotiator finds themselves on "away" territory, respecting traditions and beliefs can only help in overcoming cultural barriers and moving the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture is not limited to a national/international binary. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, corporate culture might emphasize long working hours or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, communication styles (direct versus indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, while others restrict it to "company-approved" charities or fundraisers. Looking at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, even within a company, diversity exists from region to region, including urban to suburban environments), one can appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Some cultures are not as stratified as American culture and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but this exterior is merely a sign to delve deeper.

Values are even more important to understand, as they provide the reason behind a culture. If saving face or communal harmony is valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly humiliate their company or superior to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture that places greater emphasis on a hard-driven bargain may not rush to settle the earliest opportunity. Considering these generalities before getting to the negotiating table is important, but a negotiator is well-advised to learn something about their opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation more effective.

The fool in his heart says, "There is no God." This quote first appears in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and serves as the starting point for St. Anselm's argument for the existence of God. This belief is also shared by the other author we will discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Since both arguments defend the same concept, our task is to determine which one is stronger. For the sake of brevity, let's assume that both are correct in their belief in the existence of the God of the Bible. Considering only a God-type figure that resembles the one our two authors believe in allows for a fair comparison of their arguments. However, neither truly provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

To illustrate this, let's examine St. Anselm's basic argument first. Anselm's passage suggests finding God's proof through faith, looking within oneself. He argues that because God is within our understanding, we cannot deny God's existence. While his arguments are sometimes vague, the core idea is that the proof for God lies within our own minds. He implies that we don't need external evidence to find truth about God; it's enough to examine what we inherently know. This is often referred to as faith in Christian texts.

This concept differs from St. Thomas Aquinas' view. Aquinas believes that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without needing faith. This approach would be helpful in evangelism, as it allows for recruitment of new converts through logic alone. Aquinas presents five logical arguments to support the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each argument, he shows that the proof of God's existence lies in the logical necessity for God. If you know you're missing one puzzle piece, you can infer the features and existence of the missing piece without seeing it.

Sometimes during the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would later be known as Buddha was born. Throughout his lifetime, he abandoned worldly pursuits and attained enlightenment, and his teachings gave rise to Buddhism—the purest form of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. This religion is approximately 2500 years old, and it looks quite different today compared to when Buddha was alive. This can be observed in various places, such as in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is held. Both monks and laypeople participate in this event, which holds spiritual significance despite Buddha having never taught about such a ceremony. These differences span the spectrum, from superficial traditions to the religion's core principles. The Theravada Buddhist community, whether from a monastic or lay perspective, has had to adapt its doctrinal beliefs over time. This evolution can be attributed to both internal and external influences, both hostile and benevolent.

There are several key terms that will be used frequently in this discussion. Internal forces refer to influences from members of the Buddhist community, regardless of their monastic status, while external forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, stemming from a negative perception of Buddhism. Benign forces, on the other hand, are those that do not intend to harm or help the Buddhist community but may do so inadvertently.

First, it is essential to delve into the fundamental teachings of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the Three Jewels: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is composed of the Tripitaka—the Three Baskets—of Buddhist scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the sermons, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka discusses the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. These metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence of all things). Only by recognizing these ideas can one escape Sansara, the cycle of birth and rebirth, and with it, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion), when one attains enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka also sets forth rules for laypeople and monks. Laypeople follow five precepts: I will not kill, I will not lie, I will not steal, I will not engage in sexual misconduct, and I will not consume intoxicants. Monks adhere to many more rules. The most fundamental doctrine in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: First, life is suffering (Dukkha); second, attachment causes suffering; third, suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico are a prime example of two nations that once had a long-standing rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. This rivalry reached its peak with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, gaining Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous skirmishes also occurred between the two nations, eventually subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry began with clashes over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, and a major conflict of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

This dynamic is not unique to the U.S. and Mexico; many neighboring nations have similarly enduring rivalries. David M. Pletcher (1977) observed that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting, overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Indeed, these two nations are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, unlike many other Latin American nations which have maintained good relations with the U.S.

Religious issues have been a divisive factor between the U.S. and Mexico throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that “if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy” (p.86). Similar to the Cold War, the rivalry between the U.S. and Mexico was fueled by a mix of ideological struggles and competition over vital interests, though here it was driven by religious preferences rather than political structures. This distrust was inherited from the historical enmity between the English and Spanish, hindering the establishment of friendly diplomatic relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during this 57-year rivalry, the majority of which were territorial issues involving border raids and frontier problems. Bandit and outlaw incursions from American border towns were a persistent issue until both countries exerted military control over their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to subside as Mexico became more dependent on the U.S., and it finally ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico, particularly in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I suddenly and unexpectedly became disabled by an illness of which I was previously unaware.

At the time, I was a nurse. I chose this profession because I had a strong desire for safety and security that I had lacked in my childhood. I was told, "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," which encouraged me to choose nursing despite my dreams of becoming a scientist or journalist. I was 46 and single, with no savings and unable to work. I remain disabled to this day, having lived on Social Security Disability for 15 years. I have no personal assets and live day-to-day, constantly struggling and feeling insecure. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, but I know that I could not have endured all these years without the support of my family and a few close friends. When disaster strikes, you feel very weak indeed.

My point is that life is full of emergencies, big and small. No guarantees exist, and some challenges are too great to overcome alone.

I agree that we in the U.S. should stop relying too heavily on big government. However, I believe we should learn to trust and help each other again, instead of everyone trying to fend for themselves. The early settlers did not conquer the Rockies alone; they traveled together in wagon trains. It was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources that kept them going during hard times.

While preparing for emergencies is essential, it's also crucial to get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do? Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Even in 1917, D’Arcy Thompson stated that “Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms.” The same can be said today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. The results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.)

A method for counting whorls is shown below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line, and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes i.e., builds its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have shown little change over the past decade. While Indonesia is on track to meet many Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, improvements in child and maternal health remain far from sufficient to reach the 2015 targets. Several reasons for these shortcomings will be examined below, indicating a need to bolster the health system rather than focus solely on specific intervention programs.

Indonesia has seen an increase in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% now meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions in case of complications, contributing significantly to maternal deaths due to hemorrhage. In other words, while progress in this indicator is somewhat misleading, there is still much work to be done. Additionally, the percentage of diarrhea cases in children under five treated by health professionals has decreased, and data on postnatal care services is incomplete, but it is clear that this area is a concern, with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates are still lower than expected, around 4%. The discrepancy in c-section rates between urban (7%) and rural (2%) areas underscores the issue of healthcare access, which is disproportionately focused in urban areas. Furthermore, there is a significant gap in healthcare service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, with the poor finding it much harder to access healthcare services due to out-of-pocket costs.

When discussing next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most fundamental question is how to most effectively address the lack of services. Should Indonesia adopt program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre- and postnatal care for mothers and children? Programmatic approaches are appealing as they have targeted, manageable objectives and often yield faster results. However, there are drawbacks to consider. Focusing heavily on a specific area can lead to reduced funding for other sectors and attract human resources to the better-funded area, as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS affecting family planning. Additionally, running multiple parallel programs for a single area can result in service duplication and coordination issues, leading to increased paperwork for supplies and funding.

Victorian novels are notable for their meticulous attention to detail and focus on the aristocracy of the time. Two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which incorporate elements of mystery and the bizarre, unlike most novels of the period, enriching the characters' motivations and emotions. These novels often use dreamlike sequences or dreamlike states to present this mystery, with varying content and function. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences reveal Oliver's inner turmoil, his awareness of the true nature of events, and his pain. When Oliver relives the shooting in chapter 28 as if in a dream, he struggles to find help. This scene emphasizes his lack of control over events, his deteriorating health, and his fear. The shooting itself numbs his senses, and he doesn't notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away, experiencing his despair again without the initial shock of pain. The shooting underscores Oliver's inability to control his circumstances or even attempt to do so, despite his life being in danger. A sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied, suggesting that Fagin has broken him, forcing him to accept despair and hinder his ability to react. The passage about the day passing without noticing suggests that time seems to be both prolonged and fleeting, with long periods of silence and fleeting moments of awareness.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. I did my best to help them in whatever subject they were struggling in, but my strengths were in English and reading. I was recruited by one of the instructors to help a little boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade), who was having a lot of trouble reading. It dawned on me that something was wrong; he was having the most peculiar problems. Some letters he understood how to pronounce perfectly, others, not even close, it was the strangest thing. You know, he was of Latino descent, that I was sure, but the boy spoke perfect English. We struggled from there, until the day I met his mother. I was babysitting (for lack of a better term) a few stragglers while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother walked in. His mother didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my very bad knowledge of Spanish (I was only just learning), we managed to communicate. But it was then that it hit me like a sack of bricks: Adrian could read fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if that revelation ever helped him much, but I do hope that he's doing better now.

I tell that story to address the problem of the language barrier in schools, especially here in California. I also tell it to prove that it's not always as obvious as we'd think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading it can still be a huge obstacle. I think everyone can agree that this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was fairly simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations. But for the many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There is no one answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, none of these things, by itself, will fix this problem. The key lies in combining all of the above!

First of all, the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. “Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically.” A lot of fear surrounds this idea, that it's a waste of resources, and that the majority of children in schools will reap no benefit. But that's false. If we were to apply these sorts of programs in the classroom as the rule, rather than the exception, all children would benefit from it. How do we go about this though? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and slightly unrealistic. However, I do think that there is no reason we can't have special Aids, tutors, whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

Since childhood, most people are told there is something out there bigger than themselves and beyond their comprehension. Some are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to temples, or search within themselves for the answers. Many accept the religions handed down by their parents. However, some reject them completely, denying the existence of anything beyond their own personal egocentric universe. We might adopt one set of values and later change our minds to adopt another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our own unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for light in the dark to lead us out of the shadows and into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him what his favorite type of bird was. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain pounding on the tin roof overhead while we smoked our cigarettes together. The gutters brought the rain down, drowning the plants along the edge of the porch. He looked out into the rain, his gaze half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner over the past few months and his clothes hung loosely on his body. His hair had thinned out, sparser than I remembered it. He continued to stare out into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair a little closer to his, and joined him in gazing out into the falling rain of the June twilight.

My father passed away in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation did not ease my father's suffering, but kept him alive a few more months past the doctors' projections; what value was there in him simply suffering longer I could not define. What kind of god would do this, I thought to myself. Alone in the night, I said no prayers. If god existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I did not want to watch him pass from this life into another one. So I did not. I could not watch the life that created me while it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived and not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family did, and knew Dad would not wish for his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in its essence and name, an oxymoron for 'Old-New,' as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both criticized and celebrated, accused of lacking depth, and praised for its 'terrible sublime' aspect (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, blended ideas from both "ancient and modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new literary style. Walpole combined "old" theatrical elements and 'modern' mimicry of nature in his 'modern' novels to present what he termed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws upon many throwbacks to medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication, the term "Gothic" was used to describe many different peoples, styles, and time periods, often perceived as archaic or unsophisticated in the face of "modern" societal and literary advancements. This fusion of the more theatrical "Gothic" with the new format of the novel, which allowed readers a more personal view of characters' psychology, is what has kept Gothic literature relevant for so long, making it both obsolete and new to readers far removed from its original writing.

One of the most prominent Gothic themes in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the process of training a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is particularly significant to Gothic writers because it represents the classic knight, brave, honorable, and competent, and the supposed or perceived lack of this ideal in contemporary society. Through the use of chivalric concepts and manners, the "Gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized (foreshadowing the future evolution of Gothic to Romantic) and is used to attempt to improve the present. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a time of political turmoil and was disheartened by the potential future. Immersed in politics and (arguably) unfair accusations, he may have begun to believe, however implicitly, that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" of people in the Gothic era had been lost in those individuals who comprised 'present' society. This is evident in his writing, particularly in the character of Frederic. The reader learns before meeting Frederic that he embodies many chivalric traits; he is described as:

Frederic is, foremost, a prince, has endured tragedy, and is currently presumed dead at the hands of infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course, exaggerated, bringing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess into play (66).

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from customer orders through the raw materials stage, supply, production, and distribution of products to the customer. The term supply chain management was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver. Keith Oliver described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling the operations along the supply chain to satisfy customers' needs efficiently and quickly. Six key elements of a supply chain are production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six key elements to provide the best customer service. Production is the first step in the supply chain process. Production is the foundation of the entire supply chain process. The production stage outlines when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to know what customers want. To know what customers want, managers can look at the market. The market is the biggest indicator of what customers demand. Once managers have analyzed the market and understood customer demand, they are ready to decide what products should be produced and how many of those products should be produced. After management has decided what to produce and how much, they are ready to decide where the products should be produced and which plant is best for volume and quality of goods, keeping in mind customer demand and satisfaction. After the location for production of the products has been decided, the next step is for managers to focus on scheduling workloads and maintenance of equipment. Production is a very important step in the supply chain process. Every detail is vital throughout the whole process. If every detail is not planned accordingly, it could cost the company a lot of time and money in the long run. For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores. Both companies have a design, booklet, and process for every aspect of the business. There is a designed layout of how an employee’s uniform should look and the process of receiving shipment from trucks. Having outlined processes allows a company to work smoothly without confusion of direction and expectations. The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply is defined as the strategic decisions that should be made to determine the core capabilities of a facility and outsourcing partnerships should grow from these decisions. A company may have many different divisions of production for a single product. All divisions consist of different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is the best fit for the different processes of the product. Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work to companies is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler is alive in Myanmar, the sign says.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of cardboard held above her head, the unsettling message scribbled with Sharpie onto her sign. Myanmar, also known as Burma, is a Southeastern Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta who came into power in 1962 through the act of a coup d'etat. In 2007 a number of street protests occurred, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests earned the name "The Saffron Revolution", christened after the color of the robes that the monks wore. After the first few initial uprisings the public at large began taking an interest in the protests, and while at first the Burmese government begrudgingly allowed the monks to engage in peaceful gatherings, soon the violence escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and ransacking monasteries around the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll rests at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army some days prior to the official report, is quoted as having said, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities taking place in our world, a government’s desire to quash dissent and maintain complete rule over its citizenry has been around for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive ruling over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well known examples of these actions are such incidents as the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students all gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz is significantly influenced by his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities in shaping his orchestra. Ellington's presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer, he excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that highlighted the individual talents of band members. He crafted a framework that allowed soloists to freely improvise, while also writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called upon the unique styles of band members to emphasize musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, creating coherent and original sounds tailored to each piece. Ellington's mastery of individual players' sounds, as well as how they complemented each other in an evolving ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, when discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, mentions "Creole Love Call" as an example of using voice as a jazz instrument throughout his career. This is an early instance of Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, a trait evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece consists of six choruses, as follows:

Chorus 1: A call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smoothly and melodically, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climax of the piece, where the reeds begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with a call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice takes on the sound of the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a tone color dimension to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work.

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley's playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice to create a rich and complementary sound. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington's orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something. This desire refused to be fulfilled. It began when she was about 14, just entering her teenage years. By now, she was 17, and it was still there. She had decided she wanted someone rather than a thing. Yet, she hadn't felt interested in any boys. Some had been attracted to her, made awkward attempts to woo her, but none appealed to her. She often questioned herself with this strange notion, trying to figure out what could possibly cause such a thing to happen to a teenage girl. The years of contemplation had brought up theories, but nothing substantial enough for her to really speculate on. So she lived her life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and, strangely, arguments with their daughter were very rare. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality, making her very likable in combination with the fact that she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, trying to find some new inspiration for herself, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to try to assist. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed, and she could tell her mother was in immense pain. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands, and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and illness, laced with fear. But she wasn't feeling that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off a step stool while trying to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study demonstrates that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as lower stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, and decreased consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have shown an inverse relationship between adherence to the Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial found that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. However, prior studies did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. Six times between 1984 and 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. More than 95% of nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. Cases without available records were considered "probable" and included, representing about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize random variation for individuals and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America faced a devastating financial crisis. Unemployment surged, the housing market collapsed, and many of America’s largest corporations were left in ruins. This recession continues to this day, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis happen, and how can we prevent it? In short, the financial crisis was caused by selfish and naive political decision-making that pressured banks and firms to issue subprime loans into an insufficient and immature financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to guarantee and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks lacked sufficient capital reserves and transferred this chaos to the repacked mortgages they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.

The roots of the financial crisis can be traced back to 1999 during the Clinton administration, as the president was seeking a second term. To boost his popularity, the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, setting the stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's largest home mortgage underwriter, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low- and moderate-income individuals and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its extraordinary growth in profits.” Holmes correctly predicted the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction and as Holmes foresaw, imprudent lending would certainly lead to the economy's collapse.

Multiple factors combined to send the economy into a tailspin, one of which was the new and complex mortgage structure. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were widely used in the years leading up to the crisis, further entangling various sectors of the economy in the housing market. This led to U.S. households and financial markets overexposing themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even minor price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities were left in disarray. The top five U.S. investment banks together reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at low prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose. Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was a live broadcast from NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. Her name wasn't mentioned, but his mug shot was shown, and he looked dangerous. They only spent about two minutes on this story because it was still developing. They mentioned that he had stabbed her multiple times and was arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story.

The second story was about a shooting that occurred in the Sharon Woods area early in the morning. Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old, was critically injured. No arrests had been made, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed quite brief, which might have been due to the fact that the victim was black. I've noticed over the years that minority victims of crime are often overlooked in the media. If a white child or adult is the victim, the media goes into overdrive, but if a minority person is involved, they're lucky to even be mentioned.

The next story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where the incident might have occurred. It was determined to be a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers is offering a $5,000 reward for tips leading to the arrest of the shooter.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The story was a bit too short, but they wanted to use it as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in.

They also reported a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store, wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. He was described as being about six-foot tall and weighing about 150 pounds. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his skin color and how dark he was.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. An unusual detail I noted was that instead of saying he was sentenced to 25 years in prison, they said "300" months. I'm not sure what the angle was, whether they thought that sounded harsher or not. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which I don't think was really relevant to the story.

There is an unbreakable bond between brothers; it is a bond that encompasses many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Within this bond, they understand each other better than anyone else could, and they can only see themselves reflected in their brother's eyes. It is in times of crisis that the true essence of this bond is revealed, whether it be for good or ill. When these emotions come to light, they bring with them great consequences. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal bond is accepting the repercussions they bring. When one can look into their brother's eyes and see their own reflection, they understand themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. Their true character is manifested in their actions and the consequences of those actions. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme, along with the intense emotions that accompany it. Through a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys embark on a futile journey. In the climax, bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride, and only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world, greatly influencing his actions.

The protagonist's actions can be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From their first outing together, to their final, fateful journey, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He wanted a brother to teach all his worldly skills, like holding his breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp. He wanted a brother to race to Horsehead Landing and to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn. However, Doodle's condition made all this impossible. Born with a weak heart, Doodle was unlikely to survive, let alone participate in physical activities. This was a crushing blow to the young protagonist, whose head was filled with wild dreams. He even contemplated killing Doodle by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would even consider such a thing? Yet, his heart melted when the small child smiled at him. This simple act gave the protagonist hope, showing that his resentment might not have been very strong. Deep down, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complex and creative information-processing system. As technology has evolved from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain have also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. When learning about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing begins with input from sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines simple information such as color, orientation, and the borders of the object—where there are significant color changes over a short distance—to determine that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at certain steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. In this example, top-down processing might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a certain degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. On the other hand, you might pick out your name even when it is spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
For the brain to process information, it must first store it. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are specific types of encoding for each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Huxley criticizes the impending threat of both technology and the capitalist system by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopian society in Brave New World. Its people prioritize community over individuality, and are conditioned from birth to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. Examining the work through the lens of Marxist theory reveals the author's suspicions about the development of these systems. Terms like homogenization and reification reinforce the idea that Huxley's novel is a commentary on the flaws in the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized using the Marxist concept of false consciousness. The common citizenry is prevented from understanding their true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily concerned with their own gain. This is due to ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, as evident in the conditioning of people in Brave New World. The lower classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., lack true agency; hypnopædia reinforces the desire to consume and indulge above all else, manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, or the domination of one group by another, is evident here. The lower classes are unaware of this manipulation, literally "buying into an ideology that supports that structure" (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes, born with the ability to perceive this, do little to challenge it; few Alphas or Betas, such as Bernard, do more than accept their place. The interactions between social classes are significant indicators of perceived capitalist oppression.

In Brave New World, relationships between individuals do not exist. The novel seems to refuse to distinguish characters, even among major ones, as they lack depth. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive humans of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do extreme emotions; interactions are kept superficial, evident in men's remarks about women focusing primarily on their physical appearance (i.e., pneumatic quality), and women's unashamed comments about their encounters. Each societal class's complacency with their status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effect of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to their role in the community reflects Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority so long as they continue to consume, obey, and stay in line with their peers.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. Getting around campus can be a problem for many, including myself. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room, pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in places like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad. Speaking to an alum, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today, that empty space has been filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists. I was talking to a friend who recently started bicycling again after a few years. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” Bicycling is also good for your health and the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduate students, I now live off campus, just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. Walking is also an option, but I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.
